                  display_name:
                    "I want to understand more about the stages of hairfall",
                  faq_ans:
                    'At Traya, we recognise that hair loss patterns are different for males and females; hence, we use different scales to categorise and understand the stages of hair fall in each gender. \n\nHair loss in men is often categorised using the Norwood scale, which describes different stages of male pattern baldness. Here\'s an overview of the Norwood hair loss stages with descriptions:\n\nStage 1-2: Hair Thinning and a minimal hairline recession at the temples and front side characterise this stage. It\'s a mild form of hair loss.\n\nStage 3: Stage 3 is characterised by a deeper recession at the temples, forming a more pronounced ""M"" shape. In this stage, hair loss affects the temples and the scalp\'s crown (vertex). The ""M"" shape may become more prominent.\n\nStage 4-5: Hair loss progresses further, creating a larger bald area at the vertex while the ""M"" shape continues to recede. The hairline recession at the temples and the balding at the vertex expand and may start to meet in the middle of the scalp.\n\nStage 6-7: At this stage, the bald areas at the temples and the vertex merge, leaving a hair strip around the head\'s sides and back. This is the most advanced stage, where only a narrow band of hair remains at the sides and back of the head, while the top is mostly bald.\n\nFor females, the hair scale is divided into different stages mentioned below: \n\nNo Widening: Excessive hair fall and thinner strands \nEarly Widening: When you start to see widening with less volume on the partition\nMedium Widening: Increased gap in the middle partition\nAdvanced Widening: Extreme thinning on the partition \nCoin-Sized Patches: Small bald patches on the head or other body parts',
