                  display_name:
                    "I want to understand more about the stages of hair fall",
                  faq_ans:
                    'At Traya, we understand that hair loss affects men and women differently. That\'s why we use separate scales to categorise and better grasp the stages of hair loss in each gender.\n\nAndrogenic Alopecia (Male and Female Pattern Baldness): This common genetic condition is caused by a hormone called dihydrotestosterone (DHT), which shrinks hair follicles, making them produce thinner and shorter hair until they stop producing hair altogether.\n\nTelogen Effluvium: Often triggered by stress, illness, or hormonal changes, telogen effluvium results in more hair follicles entering the resting (telogen) phase, causing hair shedding. It\'s usually a temporary condition and can be resolved when the underlying issue is addressed.\n\nA. Male Hair Loss Stages (Norwood Scale):\n\nStage 1-2 (Mild Hair Loss):\nAt this stage, men experience hair thinning which results in minimal hairline recession at the front and sides of the forehead (referred to as temples). It\'s the mildest form of hair loss, often not very noticeable.\n\nStage 3 (Moderate Hair Loss):\nHere, there\'s a more noticeable recession at the sides of the forehead (referred to as temples), forming an "M" shape. Hair loss also affects the crown (vertex), and the "M" shape may become more prominent.\n\nStage 4-5 (Advanced Hair Loss):\nHair loss continues to progress, creating a larger bald area at the vertex, while the "M" shape keeps receding. The temples and vertex balding expand and may start to meet in the middle of the scalp.\n\nStage 6-7 (Severe Hair Loss):\nIn this advanced stage, the bald areas at the temples and vertex merge, leaving a narrow strip of hair around the sides and back of the head. The top of the head becomes mostly bald.\n\nB. Female Hair Loss Stages:\nTexture Loss:\nHair starts to feel less shiny, dry, and dull. There are split ends. There may not be any loss of hair at this stage. \n\nNo Widening:\nIn this stage, women experience excessive hair fall, and their hair strands become noticeably thinner. There may be a loss of overall hair volume.\n\nEarly Widening:\nAs hair fall progresses, women may start to see the widening of their hair parting. The hair on the parting becomes sparser, resulting in a thinner appearance, especially when the hair is styled.\n\nMedium Widening:\nAt this stage, the gap in the middle of the hair parting becomes more significant. There\'s a noticeable widening of the part, and the overall volume of hair on the scalp continues to decrease.\n\nAdvanced Widening:\nExtreme thinning is observed along the hair parting. Hair may appear much thinner, and the scalp becomes more visible, leading to a significant loss of hair volume and density.\n\nCoin-Sized Patches:\nSome women may experience small bald patches on their head or other parts of the body. These patches can result from conditions like alopecia areata, which can cause hair loss in localised areas. ',
